# One Top-Level Class Per Kotlin File

- **Each public class or data class must live in its own file**, with the filename matching the class name (e.g. `RateLimitProperties` → `RateLimitProperties.kt`).
- Do **not** define multiple top-level classes in a single `.kt` file. The Kotlin Language Server cannot reliably resolve types whose name doesn't match the filename, causing false "Unresolved reference" and "annotation argument must be a compile-time constant" errors.
- Private helper classes or sealed-class subtypes co-located in the same file are fine.
